04272nam a2200553Ia 9780520401082DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20242024cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805204010827 a10.1525/97805204010822doi  a(DE-B1597)672647  a(OCoLC)1412153953  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBF175.5.P75bB44 2024 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a306.2223/eng/202312051 aBeamish, Thomas D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAfter Tragedy Strikes :bWhy Claims of Trauma and Loss Promote Public Outrage and Encourage Political Polarization /cThomas D. Beamish. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Politics of Public Tragedy -- t1. A World at Risk: Modernity, Vulnerability, and Public Tragedy -- t2. The Political Construction of Public Tragedy: Crisis and Political Communications in an Age of Blame -- t3. The Media’s Role in Public Tragedy: A New Communication Ecology, Trauma Script, and Trauma Reporting -- t4. Advocating Public Tragedy: Sympathy, Celebrity, and Tragic Harms -- tConclusion: Why Claims of Trauma and Loss Promote Public Outrage and Encourage Political Polarization -- tAppendix: Notes on Data Collection and Media Analysis -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile trauma and loss can occur anywhere, most suffering is experienced as personal tragedy. Yet some tragedies transcend everyday life's sad but inevitable traumas to become notorious public events: de facto ";public"; tragedies. In these crises, suffering is made publicly visible and lamentable. Such tragedies are defined by public accusations, social blame, outpourings of grief and anger, spontaneous memorialization, and collective action. These, in turn, generate a comparable set of political reactions, including denial, denunciation, counterclaims, blame avoidance, and a competition to control memories of the event. Disasters and crises are no more or less common today than in the past, but public tragedies now seem ubiquitous. After Tragedy Strikes argues that they are now epochal—public tragedies have become the day's definitive social and political events. Thomas D. Beamish deftly explores this phenomenon by developing the historical context within which these events occur and the role that political elites, the media, and an emergent ideology of victimhood have played in cultivating their ascendence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aPsychic trauma and mass mediazUnited Statesy21st century. 0aPsychic traumaxPolitical aspectszUnited Statesy21st century. 0aPsychic traumaxSocial aspectszUnited Statesy21st century. 0aSecondary traumatic stressxPolitical aspectszUnited Statesy21st century. 0aSecondary traumatic stressxSocial aspectszUnited Statesy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079135840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520401082?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520401082423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520401082/original  a978-3-11-079135-8  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles